The Java Collections Framework (JCF) is a unified architecture to store, manipulate, and process groups of objects.
It belongs to java.util package and provides interfaces, implementations (classes), and algorithms (methods).

Core Hierarchy of Collections:
      Iterable
         ↓
      Collection
         ├── List
         ├── Set
         └── Queue
              └── Deque
Map (separate hierarchy, not part of Collection)

Collection Interface:
  Common Methods (available in all collections):
    add(E e)
    remove(Object o)
    size()
    isEmpty()
    contains(Object o)
    clear()
    iterator()

List Interface:
    List is a child of Collection.
    Key Characteristics:
          Maintains insertion order
          Allows duplicate elements
          Supports index-based access
          Allows null values
   Main Implementations of List
      🔹 1. ArrayList
      🔹 2. LinkedList
      🔹 3. Vector (Legacy)
      🔹 4. Stack (extends Vector)
   Common Methods in List
        add(E e)
        add(int index, E element)
        get(int index)
        set(int index, E element)
        remove(int index)
        remove(Object o)
        size()
        contains(Object o)
        indexOf(Object o)
        lastIndexOf(Object o)
        clear()

  1. ArrayList –
    🔹 Structure:
          Backed by dynamic array
          transient Object[] elementData;
    🔹 How It Works
        Step 1: Initialization - ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>(); Default capacity = 10
        Step 2: Adding Elements - list.add(10); Stored in array index
        Step 3: Resize (Growth Mechanism) - When capacity is full:
                New Capacity = Old Capacity + (Old Capacity / 2)
                             = 1.5x growth
                              10 → 15 → 22 → 33 → ...
    
      Internally:  Arrays.copyOf()
                  [10, 20, 30, null, null...]
                           ↓
                        add(40)
                           ↓
                  [10, 20, 30, 40, null...]

    🔹 Time Complexity
            Operation	    Time
            get()	        O(1)
            add()	        O(1) (amortized)
            remove()	    O(n)
            insert middle	O(n)

 2. LinkedList:
    LinkedList implements: List, Deque, Queue. That means:
      It works as List
      Also works as Queue
      Also works as Deque
    Internal Working
        Structure: Doubly Linked List
        class Node {
            E item;
            Node next;
            Node prev;
        }
        Representation: null <- [10] <-> [20] <-> [30] -> null
    Key Operations:
        Add:
            list.add(10);
            list.addFirst(5);
            list.addLast(20);
        Remove:
            list.remove();
            list.removeFirst();
            list.removeLast();
        Access:
            list.get(1);
  Internal Behavior:
    Adding → link new node
    Removing → update pointers
    No shifting like ArrayList
   Time Complexity:
        Operation	    Time
        add()	        O(1)
        remove()	    O(1)
        get()	        O(n)
  
  LinkedList can act as:Stack, Queue and Deque

3.Vector
🔹 Definition:
      Legacy class
      Same as ArrayList but thread-safe
      Vector<Integer> v = new Vector<>();
🔹 Internal Working:
      Uses array
      Automatically resizes
      All methods are synchronized
🔹 Key Methods:
      add()
      get()
      remove()
      size()
🔹 Drawback: Slower due to synchronization

4.Stack: 
    follows LIFO (Last In First Out)
    Push → Add element
    Pop  → Remove last element
    Peek → View top element
    There are 3 main ways to use Stack:
       1. Legacy Stack Class - Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();
       2. Deque (Recommended) - Deque<Integer> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
       3. LinkedList as Stack -  Deque<Integer> stack = new LinkedList<>();
    
  Stack Class (Legacy): public class Stack<E> extends Vector<E>
                        It is synchronized (thread-safe)
                        Slower due to locking
          🔹 Methods:
                  push(E item)
                  pop()
                  peek()
                  isEmpty()
                  search(Object o)

                  Stack<Integer> s = new Stack<>();
                  s.push(10);
                  s.push(20);
                  s.push(30);
                  System.out.println(s.pop());  // 30
                  System.out.println(s.peek()); // 20

          Internal Working of Stack:  
                  Since Stack extends Vector, internally: Uses Dynamic Array
                            Object[] elementData;
                    🔹 Push Operation:
                            Before: [10, 20]
                            push(30)
                            After:  [10, 20, 30]
                            Adds element at top (end of array)
                    🔹 Pop Operation
                            Before: [10, 20, 30]
                            pop()
                            After:  [10, 20]
                            Removes last element
                    🔹 Resize Mechanism - Same as ArrayList: New Capacity = Old + (Old / 2)
                    🔹 Time Complexity
                            Operation	  Time
                            push()	    O(1)
                            pop()	      O(1)
                            peek()	    O(1)
      Why Stack is NOT Recommended ❗
      Problems:
          Synchronized → slow
          Legacy class
          Extends Vector (bad design)
    
  Modern Stack (Using Deque) :
    🔹 Best Practice:
          Deque<Integer> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
    🔹 Methods Mapping:
          Stack	    Deque
          push()	  addFirst()
          pop()	    removeFirst()
          peek()	  peekFirst()
    🔹 Example
          Deque<Integer> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
          stack.push(10);
          stack.push(20);    
          System.out.println(stack.pop()); // 20
    🔹 Internal Working (ArrayDeque) 
          Uses Resizable Circular Array
          
          [ _, _, 10, 20, _ ]
                  ↑ head
          No shifting
          Uses head/tail pointers

    🔹 Why Faster?
          No synchronization
          Better memory usage
          No legacy overhead

Types of Stack (Conceptual)
    🔹 1. Array-based Stack
          Used in Stack, ArrayDeque
          Fast access
    🔹 2. Linked List Stack
            class Node {
                int data;
                Node next;
            }
            Dynamic size
            No resizing
    🔹 3. Concurrent Stack
            Thread-safe version Example: ConcurrentLinkedDeque
  
  Real-Time Usage of Stack
    🔹 1. Function Call Stack (JVM) -> Stored in stack memory
              main()
                → methodA()
                     → methodB()    
    🔹 2. Expression Evaluation
            Infix → Postfix
            (2 + 3) * 4
    🔹 3. Undo / Redo
            Text editor
            Browser history
    🔹 4. Balanced Parentheses
            if(ch == '(') push
            if(ch == ')') pop
    🔹 5. DFS (Depth First Search)
              Graph traversal
              Backtracking
    🔹 6. Backtracking Problems
              Maze solving
              Recursion simulation
    
    1. Why remove is slow? Because elements are shifted
    2. Is LinkedList a List or Queue?  BOTH ✅
    3. Why ArrayList is faster than LinkedList? -> Direct index access (array)
    4. How ArrayList grows? -> 1.5x resizing using Arrays.copyOf()
    5. Why LinkedList uses more memory? -> Stores prev + next pointers
    6. Which is better for insert in middle? -> LinkedList (no shifting)
    7. Why Stack is not recommended? ->Legacy + synchronized → slow
    8. Difference: Queue vs Deque?
             Queue → one end
             Deque → both ends
    9. Best replacement for Stack? -> ArrayDeque
    10. Why use Deque instead of Stack? -> Faster + non-legacy + no synchronization
    11. Is Stack thread-safe? -> Yes (because Vector)
    12.  Can LinkedList be used as Stack?  Yes. Deque<Integer> stack = new LinkedList<>();
